WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:11.200
My name is Rebecca Hadi and I'm here today to tell you about a time that I crashed a

00:00:11.200 --> 00:00:18.000
database and I learned some techniques to help from ever doing that again that I'm going

00:00:18.000 --> 00:00:21.000
to share with you.

00:00:21.000 --> 00:00:26.120
I was working on the 31st floor of an office building in downtown Seattle that had a beautiful

00:00:26.120 --> 00:00:29.920
view of the Puget Sound and Olympic Mountains.

00:00:29.920 --> 00:00:35.119
I was working on the marketing analytics team at a large fashion retailer and I was working

00:00:35.119 --> 00:00:41.119
on a project that involved migrating marketing attribution reporting from our old Clickstream

00:00:41.119 --> 00:00:46.320
vendor to an in-house solution.

00:00:46.320 --> 00:00:48.700
This involved doing a backfill.

00:00:48.700 --> 00:00:51.680
Has anyone in the room ever done a data backfill?

00:00:51.680 --> 00:00:55.099
Yeah, I see a few hands.

00:00:55.099 --> 00:00:59.520
Has anyone ever had performance issues with that backfill?

00:00:59.520 --> 00:01:02.360
I certainly have.

00:01:02.360 --> 00:01:08.440
So this project required a backfill of a year and a half of historical Clickstream data.

00:01:08.440 --> 00:01:13.199
But at this time, I had been a data analyst for about three years and through that time

00:01:13.199 --> 00:01:16.760
had written SQL queries almost every day.

00:01:16.760 --> 00:01:20.279
So naturally, I thought I was an expert.

00:01:20.279 --> 00:01:27.879
So I sat down at my desk, put on my headphones, turned on a score by Trent Reznor and got

00:01:27.879 --> 00:01:33.720
to work.

00:01:33.720 --> 00:01:39.599
I was working in an Amazon Redshift database with page view level website data.

00:01:39.599 --> 00:01:44.559
And for those of you who may not be familiar with website data, any time that you hover

00:01:44.559 --> 00:01:48.199
or click or view a page, it's generating data.

00:01:48.199 --> 00:01:53.400
So you can imagine that that can be a pretty large set of data for a single person, not

00:01:53.400 --> 00:01:57.680
to mention a website that has millions of visitors a year.

00:01:57.680 --> 00:02:00.320
In the past, I had worked at health insurance companies.

00:02:00.320 --> 00:02:03.800
And so I was used to working with medical claims data.

00:02:03.800 --> 00:02:08.679
And that data was more in the millions of rows.

00:02:08.679 --> 00:02:14.160
This data set was 4 billion rows.

00:02:14.160 --> 00:02:20.639
So I had my query and I sat down on my desk and I had my two monitors.

00:02:20.639 --> 00:02:25.559
On the right-hand side, I had my SQL IDE and I set off my backfill.

00:02:25.559 --> 00:02:30.440
And on my left monitor, I had some documentation open that I was working on.

00:02:30.440 --> 00:02:32.800
I updated some JIRA tickets.

00:02:32.800 --> 00:02:35.839
And let's be honest, check my Twitter feed.

00:02:35.839 --> 00:02:40.479
After getting sucked into that for about 45 minutes, I turned to my screen and I noticed

00:02:40.479 --> 00:02:43.500
that my query was still running.

00:02:43.500 --> 00:02:50.240
And I thought, hmm, that doesn't seem very good.

00:02:50.240 --> 00:02:53.000
So I tried to cancel it.

00:02:53.000 --> 00:02:58.639
And I got the rainbow wheel of death and had to kill it.

00:02:58.639 --> 00:03:01.240
And then I tried to run it again.

00:03:01.240 --> 00:03:05.559
And about an hour later, there was still a problem.

00:03:05.559 --> 00:03:08.720
So I tried to cancel it again.

00:03:08.720 --> 00:03:10.880
And again, it crashed.

00:03:10.880 --> 00:03:14.080
So I thought to myself, what is going on with this?

00:03:14.080 --> 00:03:20.600
I'm a SQL expert and obviously my code is perfect so it can't be anything that I'm doing.

00:03:20.600 --> 00:03:25.520
On the 31st floor, it held the entire data science and analytics team, which was about

00:03:25.520 --> 00:03:30.399
100 people made up of data analysts, engineers, and scientists.

00:03:30.399 --> 00:03:34.440
So I thought, it's probably just a busy time on the database.

00:03:34.440 --> 00:03:39.919
I'm probably running into some concurrency issues and it's just slow in general.

00:03:39.919 --> 00:03:41.919
Then I had a brilliant idea.

00:03:42.000 --> 00:03:44.479
I'll just run it at night.

00:03:44.479 --> 00:03:48.919
Traffic on the database will be low and everything will be fine.

00:03:48.919 --> 00:03:54.240
So I went home, took the bus, and before I went to bed that night, I set off my query

00:03:54.240 --> 00:03:59.440
to run into the night.

00:03:59.440 --> 00:04:05.800
I woke up a little bit early the next morning to a Slack notification on my phone from the

00:04:05.800 --> 00:04:15.479
database administrator who had never direct messaged me before.

00:04:15.479 --> 00:04:20.440
And all it said was, hi.

00:04:20.440 --> 00:04:24.279
Oh, fudge, what have I done?

00:04:24.279 --> 00:04:27.279
My heart sank because I knew that something was wrong.

00:04:27.279 --> 00:04:32.480
It turned out that the query that I ran ran for over seven hours.

00:04:32.480 --> 00:04:37.200
And not only that, it took compute resources from other nightly ETL jobs, which made them

00:04:37.200 --> 00:04:42.679
run slower, which made them finish later, which ended up delaying all of our business

00:04:42.679 --> 00:04:45.559
reporting for that day.

00:04:45.559 --> 00:04:46.920
I was mortified.

00:04:46.920 --> 00:04:52.760
I had not only made my life harder, I had made the database administrator's life harder,

00:04:52.760 --> 00:04:57.239
my team's life harder because their stakeholders' reporting was delayed as well.

00:04:57.239 --> 00:05:01.920
And needless to say, the business was not very happy with me.

00:05:01.920 --> 00:05:07.760
But lucky for me, the DBA reached out to me and offered to help me rewrite this query.

00:05:07.760 --> 00:05:13.679
So I swallowed my pride, walked down to the 25th floor where the engineering team sat,

00:05:13.679 --> 00:05:20.559
pulled up a chair, and had a one-hour meeting that changed the course of my SQL life forever.

00:05:20.559 --> 00:05:26.359
And what I learned, I'm going to share with you today.

00:05:26.359 --> 00:05:30.880
Imagine for a second that you're going to explore a dark cave.

00:05:30.880 --> 00:05:36.880
What items might you want to help you?

00:05:36.880 --> 00:05:38.640
For me, I would want a map.

00:05:38.640 --> 00:05:41.239
I would want to know where I'm going.

00:05:41.239 --> 00:05:43.200
Does this cave even have an exit?

00:05:43.200 --> 00:05:46.720
How many tunnels are there?

00:05:46.720 --> 00:05:49.839
I would also want a team or a cavern crew.

00:05:49.839 --> 00:05:56.200
I would want people to help carry equipment and make the journey easier.

00:05:56.200 --> 00:05:59.880
It's also very dark in this cave, so a flashlight would be helpful to be able to see where I'm

00:05:59.880 --> 00:06:05.279
going.

00:06:05.279 --> 00:06:08.040
An explain plan is like a map.

00:06:08.040 --> 00:06:16.600
It returns a step-by-step list of actions that your query will take to return your dataset.

00:06:16.600 --> 00:06:22.920
It also returns the estimated computational cost of that query.

00:06:22.920 --> 00:06:24.160
It's very easy to run.

00:06:24.160 --> 00:06:30.640
You only have to put the word explain in front of your query and run it.

00:06:30.640 --> 00:06:33.440
The first time I saw an explain plan, I was very overwhelmed.

00:06:33.440 --> 00:06:36.040
I swear my head exploded.

00:06:36.040 --> 00:06:41.720
But it turns out that it's a very helpful tool because that computational cost can help

00:06:41.720 --> 00:06:46.559
you understand if changes that you're making to your query are helpful.

00:06:46.559 --> 00:06:53.040
So in my instance, where I would run my query, wait an hour, kill it, run it, wait an hour,

00:06:53.040 --> 00:07:00.440
kill it, if I had run explain plans, I could see that the changes that I was making would

00:07:00.440 --> 00:07:04.600
reduce the computational cost without having to wait that extra hour.

00:07:04.600 --> 00:07:10.880
So explain plans are very useful.

00:07:10.880 --> 00:07:18.260
For our cavern crew or cave team, we want everyone to be contributing equally.

00:07:18.260 --> 00:07:22.760
We don't want one person to be carrying all of the backpacks and the other people to not

00:07:22.760 --> 00:07:24.440
be carrying anything.

00:07:24.440 --> 00:07:30.079
That doesn't seem, one, very nice, or two, very efficient.

00:07:30.079 --> 00:07:35.859
From a query perspective, compute nodes are like your cave team.

00:07:35.859 --> 00:07:43.420
You want all of your compute nodes contributing equally and leveraging all of their resources.

00:07:43.420 --> 00:07:51.040
To make sure that happens, you need to appropriately specify the distribution style.

00:07:51.040 --> 00:07:55.779
Distribution means that your data is properly distributed across the compute nodes and

00:07:55.779 --> 00:08:01.299
does not have significant skew.

00:08:01.299 --> 00:08:02.540
But how do you do that?

00:08:02.540 --> 00:08:06.779
How do you know what's the right distribution style?

00:08:06.779 --> 00:08:13.660
You think about which column you're going to join on.

00:08:13.660 --> 00:08:20.660
If you're planning on joining on a unique ID, such as an order ID or a customer ID,

00:08:20.660 --> 00:08:24.320
then dist style key is what you want to use.

00:08:24.320 --> 00:08:29.880
And the choice of your dist key depends on which column you are going to use to join

00:08:29.880 --> 00:08:33.559
to another dataset.

00:08:33.559 --> 00:08:37.520
Dist style all is very dangerous.

00:08:37.520 --> 00:08:41.880
It copies your data across each of the compute nodes.

00:08:41.880 --> 00:08:47.400
So in the case where you're not going to join your table to anything ever and it's a small

00:08:47.820 --> 00:08:54.580
dataset, you can get away with dist style all, but I personally wouldn't recommend it.

00:08:54.580 --> 00:08:58.979
And if you're not sure what you're going to join on, maybe you have a table that's a lot

00:08:58.979 --> 00:09:06.059
of rows, but it doesn't have a good unique ID or a candidate for a dist key, and maybe

00:09:06.059 --> 00:09:10.979
it's a combination of fields that's making it have a lot of rows, then dist style even

00:09:10.979 --> 00:09:13.739
is a good candidate.

00:09:13.739 --> 00:09:19.400
And the beauty of the explain plan is that when we make these changes to our table and

00:09:19.400 --> 00:09:24.440
try to run our query, we can run an explain plan to know if those changes actually made

00:09:24.440 --> 00:09:31.159
a difference.

00:09:31.159 --> 00:09:37.460
So caution with dist style all.

00:09:37.460 --> 00:09:40.119
Your sort key is like a flashlight.

00:09:40.119 --> 00:09:43.679
It helps you only search relevant data.

00:09:43.700 --> 00:09:51.260
Imagine that you have a dataset that has three years of data, 2020, 2021, and 2022.

00:09:51.260 --> 00:09:52.580
I only care about 2022.

00:09:52.580 --> 00:09:54.219
I'm living in the present.

00:09:54.219 --> 00:10:00.900
So I have a where clause that filters on where year equals 2022.

00:10:00.900 --> 00:10:03.580
And my result set would be filtered.

00:10:03.580 --> 00:10:11.059
However, if I'm not, if the table I'm querying from does not have a sort key, even though

00:10:11.159 --> 00:10:18.799
my result set is filtered, the query had to scan the entire table to find it, which is

00:10:18.799 --> 00:10:21.400
not very efficient.

00:10:21.400 --> 00:10:25.640
And so when you specify a sort key, it helps your query know immediately where to find

00:10:25.640 --> 00:10:30.880
the data that you're looking for, so it reduces the computation needed to pull back your result

00:10:30.880 --> 00:10:35.200
set.

00:10:35.200 --> 00:10:40.039
To decide on a sort key, you think about which column you will filter on.

00:10:40.039 --> 00:10:45.940
A lot of times that's a date.

00:10:45.940 --> 00:10:49.580
This is an example of the dataset that I was working with on that fateful night when I

00:10:49.580 --> 00:10:51.820
ruined everything.

00:10:51.820 --> 00:10:58.080
There's a user ID, a session ID, an event ID, and an event time.

00:10:58.080 --> 00:11:01.260
There's also an event type and a marketing tag.

00:11:01.260 --> 00:11:06.260
I was working on the marketing analytics team, and so I cared about traffic and sales driven

00:11:06.260 --> 00:11:07.260
by marketing.

00:11:08.260 --> 00:11:13.599
Based on what we just learned, we know that distribution style key is a good fit for this

00:11:13.599 --> 00:11:18.099
table because it has unique identifiers.

00:11:18.099 --> 00:11:25.059
But which unique identifier would we choose as a dist key?

00:11:25.059 --> 00:11:28.219
The answer is it depends.

00:11:28.219 --> 00:11:33.940
If I was keeping the dataset at this level, I would want to specify the dist key as the

00:11:33.940 --> 00:11:37.179
most granular ID.

00:11:37.859 --> 00:11:43.539
Using this dataset, I would likely join on the event ID to another table.

00:11:43.539 --> 00:11:49.460
So therefore, it should be the dist key.

00:11:49.460 --> 00:11:54.820
Pulling together everything that we have learned, on the left-hand side, I have a query that

00:11:54.820 --> 00:11:59.859
takes that page view level data that we were just looking at and aggregates it to the session

00:11:59.859 --> 00:12:02.020
level.

00:12:02.020 --> 00:12:06.419
If you can imagine landing on a website, you can have multiple page views during a session,

00:12:06.419 --> 00:12:12.059
and so I cared about what marketing is at the session level.

00:12:12.059 --> 00:12:18.539
And so when I'm creating this temporary table, I've specified my distribution style as key,

00:12:18.539 --> 00:12:23.419
and I've specified my dist key as session ID because that's what I'm going to use to

00:12:23.419 --> 00:12:26.059
join to another dataset.

00:12:26.059 --> 00:12:31.340
So I know that all my compute nodes will be contributing equally.

00:12:31.340 --> 00:12:36.780
I also have my flashlight or my sort key on session start time because that's what

00:12:36.780 --> 00:12:45.000
I'm going to use when I end up filtering from this temporary table.

00:12:45.000 --> 00:12:49.900
On the right, I have a query that leverages the table that I just created and joins it

00:12:49.900 --> 00:12:54.539
to another table called web orders.

00:12:54.539 --> 00:13:00.539
And I'm joining to that table on user ID and session ID.

00:13:01.539 --> 00:13:07.739
Because we have specified session ID as a distribution key, all of the compute nodes

00:13:07.739 --> 00:13:14.179
will be used in this join, and it will make it run much more efficiently.

00:13:14.179 --> 00:13:18.960
Because we have the sort key specified as session start time, I'm filtering on anything

00:13:18.960 --> 00:13:25.900
greater than January 1st of 2022, and so therefore, my query doesn't have to search for data that

00:13:25.900 --> 00:13:27.900
it doesn't care about.

00:13:27.900 --> 00:13:34.859
And we've saved time there as well.

00:13:34.859 --> 00:13:36.679
We've run our query.

00:13:36.679 --> 00:13:41.380
We have our results set in a reasonable amount of time.

00:13:41.380 --> 00:13:46.179
We've made it to the light at the end of the tunnel on the other side of the cave, which

00:13:46.179 --> 00:13:51.739
is a big win.

00:13:51.739 --> 00:13:54.739
Some other wins that came out of this experience.

00:13:54.739 --> 00:14:00.780
For one, my query that had run overnight for seven hours ended up running in under

00:14:00.780 --> 00:14:04.140
one hour during a high traffic time on the database.

00:14:04.140 --> 00:14:10.059
So ultimately, the runtime was reduced by six hours because of these changes.

00:14:10.059 --> 00:14:15.419
I also built a strong relationship with the database administrator that was very useful

00:14:15.419 --> 00:14:20.059
for future cross-functional projects between the data science team and the engineering

00:14:20.059 --> 00:14:23.020
team.

00:14:23.059 --> 00:14:32.619
My favorite lesson came from I documented my findings and I shared it back with my team.

00:14:32.619 --> 00:14:39.219
I helped them learn these techniques and apply them to their own queries to avoid making

00:14:39.219 --> 00:14:42.140
the mistakes that I made.

00:14:42.140 --> 00:14:48.140
And through that process of sharing my experience with my team, it also helped me have a paradigm

00:14:48.179 --> 00:14:51.700
shift towards embracing mistakes.

00:14:51.700 --> 00:15:04.260
Because mistakes, even very business negative impacting ones, can help you learn a lot.

00:15:04.260 --> 00:15:10.179
So if you find yourself with a long-running query, there are a few things you can do.

00:15:10.179 --> 00:15:12.940
You can run an explain plan.

00:15:12.940 --> 00:15:15.539
You can check the distribution style.

00:15:15.539 --> 00:15:18.260
And you can specify sort keys.

00:15:18.260 --> 00:15:22.940
And that is how you can save hours of time with just a few lines of code.

00:15:22.940 --> 00:15:23.979
Thank you.

